%[text] Chucktown Bank currently has two tellers on duty during regular business hours. 
%[text] Customers arrive according to a Poisson process at a mean rate of 40 per hour. 
%[text] Since customers arrive at a constant rate of 40 per hour regardless of the queue length, 
%[text] lambda\_n = lambda = 40
lambda = 40;
%%
%[text] The time required to serve a customer has an exponential distribution 
%[text] with a mean of 2 minutes. So mu = 60 minutes /2
%[text] mu\_n = mu = 30
%%
mu = 30;
%[text] Use an M/M/2 queue model.
%[text] Information for this assignment was taken from the M/M/k example on page 539 and 542.
%[text] n = 0,1,2
%[text] $\\mu\_n =n\\;\\mu =\\left\\lbrace 0,30,60\\right\\rbrace${"editStyle":"visual"}
%%
s=2;
%%
%[text] rho = lambda/(2 mu) = 40/(2\*30) = 2/3 = .66
%%
rho = lambda/(2* mu) ;
%%
%[text] 
%[text] From page 542.
%[text] **3. Find the theoretical values of the following steady-state parameters:**
%[text] **5. How well do the theoretical results agree with the statistics calculated from the simulation?  Express the discrepancy as a percentage of the theoretical value.**
%[text] 
%[text] **P\_n: probability of exactly 𝑛 customers at this bank; give numerical values for 0 ≤ 𝑛 ≤ 5**
%[text] $\\begin{array}{l}\nP\_0 ={\\left\\lbrack 1+\\frac{\\lambda }{\\mu }+\\frac{(\\frac{\\lambda }{\\mu })^2 }{2!(1-\\frac{\\lambda }{2\\mu })}\\right\\rbrack }^{\\;-1} ={\\left\\lbrack 1+\\frac{40}{30}+\\frac{(\\frac{40}{30})^2 }{2!(1-\\frac{40}{2\*30})}\\right\\rbrack }^{\\;-1} ={\\left\\lbrack \\frac{30+40}{30}+\\frac{\\frac{{40}^2 }{{30}^2 }}{\\frac{4}{6}}\\right\\rbrack }^{\\;-1} \\;\\\\\n={\\left\\lbrack \\frac{70}{30}+\\frac{6\*40\*40}{4\*30\*30}\\right\\rbrack }^{\\;-1} ={\\left\\lbrack \\frac{7}{3}+\\frac{10\*4}{5\*3}\\right\\rbrack }^{\\;-1} ={\\left\\lbrack \\frac{7}{3}+\\frac{8}{3}\\right\\rbrack }^{\\;-1} ={\\left\\lbrack \\frac{15}{3}\\right\\rbrack }^{\\;-1} \\;\\approx \\;\\ldotp 2\\;\\;\\;\\;\n\\end{array}${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] **0 ≤ 𝑛 ≤ 5**
%[text] $P\_n =2\\;{\\left(\\frac{\\lambda \\;}{\\mu {\\;}\_2 }\\right)}^n P\_0 =2\\;{\\left(\\frac{40\\;}{60}\\right)}^n \\left(0\\ldotp 2\\right)${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $P\_1 =2\\;{\\left(\\frac{40\\;}{60}\\right)}^1 \\left(0\\ldotp 2\\right)\\approx 0\\ldotp 2667\\;\\;\\;${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $P\_2 =2\\;{\\left(\\frac{40\\;}{60}\\right)}^2 \\left(0\\ldotp 2\\right)\\approx 0\\ldotp 1778${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $P\_3 =2\\;{\\left(\\frac{40\\;}{60}\\right)}^3 \\left(0\\ldotp 2\\right)\\;\\approx 0\\ldotp 1185\\;\\;\\;\\;${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $P\_4 =2\\;{\\left(\\frac{40\\;}{60}\\right)}^4 \\left(0\\ldotp 2\\right)\\approx 0\\ldotp 0790\\;\\;${"editStyle":"visual"}
%[text] $P\_5 =2\\;{\\left(\\frac{40\\;}{60}\\right)}^5 \\left(0\\ldotp 2\\right)\\;\\;\\approx 0\\ldotp 0527${"editStyle":"visual"} 
%[text] 
%[text] These are the outputs from the first histogram shown later (the one with red dots). 
%[text] The red dots are the theoretical calculations (which are computed in the manner as shown above in Latex and in the code as specified).
%[text] The blue parts or y values are shown below (and can also be found in the code as specified). 
%[text] `P(0) = 0.205289`
%[text] `P(1) = 0.267361`
